DATA DRIVEN BUILDING SIMULATION¶

This project is made by Funaro Eleonora, Romanelli Alessia and Rossetti Federica.

In this project we are request to apply Machine Learning to a given dataset. We choose the SMLsystem that is an house built at the Universidad CEU Cardenal Herrera (CEU-UCH) to participate in the Solar Decathlon 2012 competition. A predictive module, based on artificial neural networks (ANNs), has been developed using data acquired in Valencia. The module produces short-term forecast of indoor tempreature, using as input data captured by a complex monitoring system.

Let's start importing phyton library needed to develope the code.

def lag_column(df,column_name,lag_period=1):
    for i in range(1,lag_period+1,1):
        new_column_name = column_name+" -"+str(i)+"hr"
        df[new_column_name]=(df[column_name]).shift(i)
    return df

    for i in range(lag_start, lag_end+1, lag_interval):
        new_column_name=column_name+" -"+str(i)+"hr"
        print new_column_name

        df.dropna(inplace=True)
    return df

Machine learning¶

Now we are applying machine learning to the given data. With Machine learning we create mathematical models to help analyzing data. Once these models have been fit to previously seen datas, they can be used to predict and understand aspects of new datas.

To do this we have to divide our data in two macro categories: Training set and Test set. Training set is the part of data used to create the model and it's a list of pratictal examples in which we build the algorithm. The Test set is instead the part of data used to verify that the model works.

These forecasting measures could allow, in our case, the house to adapt itself to future temperature conditions by using home automation in an energy efficient manner. The first method available is Linear Regression.

Linear regression model¶

The linear regression is a statistic process looking for a relationship between two or more variables. Scikit-learn is a free software machine learning library for the Python programming language. Features represents the input and Target is the output. In this case we use a size of 0,2. This means that the training set is made by the 20 % of data choosen randomly.

In [15]:
Target=FinalDatabase["TempRoom_normalized"] 
Features=FinalDatabase.drop("TempRoom_normalized",axis=1)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(Features,Target,test_size = 0.2, random_state=41234)
In [16]:
from sklearn import linear_model
linear_reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()

linear_reg.fit(X_train, Y_train)
predicted_linearReg_split = linear_reg.predict(X_test)

predicted_DF_linearReg_split=pd.DataFrame(predicted_linearReg_split,index=Y_test.index, columns=["RoomTemp_linearReg"])
predicted_DF_linearReg_split=predicted_DF_linearReg_split.join(Y_test)

Cross validation¶

To choose more accurately our training set, we use k-fold cross validation. In this way we dont't choose random datas but we divide our total database in k parts.At any step, the kth part of the dataset becomes the validation set, the remaining is the training set.

In [87]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_predict
predict_CV = cross_val_predict(linear_reg,Features,Target,cv=10)
predicted_DF_CV=pd.DataFrame(predict_CV,index=Target.index,columns=["RoomTemp_CV"])
predicted_DF_CV=predicted_DF_CV.join(Target)
predicted_DF_CV_SelectedPeriod=predicted_DF_CV["2012-03-15 00:00:00":"2012-03-18 23:00:00"]
predicted_DF_CV_SelectedPeriod.plot()
